quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The do...while Loop[/h1]

Unlike [b]for [/b]and [b]while [/b]loops, which test the loop condition at the top of the loop, the [b]do...while[/b] loop checks its condition at the bottom of the loop.
A[b] do...while[/b] loop is similar to a [b]while [/b]loop. The one difference is that the [b]do...while[/b] loop is guaranteed to execute [b]at least one time[/b].
[b]Syntax:[/b] [code format="cpp"][b]do [/b]{
   statement(s);
} [b]while [/b](condition);[/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print x variable's values 10 times.
[!raw!]
int x = 0;
do {
  cout << x << endl;
  x++;
} 
{0} (x < {1});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The do...while Loop[/h1]

Here is an example: [code format="cpp" codeId="206"]int a = 0;
[b]do [/b]{
  cout << a << endl;
  a++;
} [b]while[/b](a < 5);

/* Outputs
0
1
2
3
4
*/[/code]
[note]Don't forget the [b]semicolon[/b] after the while statement.[/note]

[h1]while vs. do...while[/h1]

If the condition evaluated to [b]false[/b], the statements in the [b]do [/b]would still run once: [code format="cpp" codeId="207"]int a = 42;
do {
  cout << a << endl;
  a++;
} while(a < 5);

// Outputs 42[/code]
[note]The [b]do...while[/b] loop executes the statements at least once, and then tests the condition.
The [b]while [/b]loop executes the statement after testing condition.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print "this is a loop" to the screen 15 times.
[!raw!]
int x = 1;
do {
  cout << "this is a loop" << endl;
  x++;
} 
while ({0} <= {1});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The do...while Loop[/h1]

As with other loops, if the condition in the loop never evaluates to [b]false[/b], the loop will run forever.
For example: [code format="cpp" codeId="940"]int a = 42;
do {
  cout << a << endl;
} while (a > 0);[/code]
This will print 42 to the screen [b]forever[/b].
[note]Always test your loops, so you know that they operate in the manner you expect.[/note]
